 Newsflash. Awards, new books, film deals… it's all here!\r\n\r\n","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/series/newsflash","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/childrens-books-site/series/newsflash","sectionName":"Children's books","references":[]},{"id":"books/carnegie-medal","sectionId":"books","webTitle":"Carnegie medal","type":"keyword","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/carnegie-medal","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/carnegie-medal","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"type/article","webTitle":"Article","type":"type","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/articles","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/type/article","references":[]}],"references":[]},{"webPublicationDate":"2016-03-15T16:59:18Z","webTitle":"Animal travellers: a history of exotic animals in the UK – in pictures","sectionId":"books","type":"gallery","rights":{"syndicatable":"false"},"id":"books/gallery/2016/mar/15/animal-travellers-a-history-of-exotic-animals-in-the-uk-in-pictures","fields":{"commentable":"true","byline":"Caroline Grigson","headline":"Animal travellers: a history of exotic animals in the UK – in pictures","trailText":"Exotic animals have been kept in Britain for more than eight centuries, inspiring wonder and terror in those who saw them – despite the cruelties of their captivity. The zoologist Caroline Grigson takes us on a tour of the UK’s historic animal visitors, from agouti to zebra","productionOffice":"UK","body":"<figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"1b3e9a15a341e2dd2a947c2dc5a13b8ae20c1c73\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/1b3e9a15a341e2dd2a947c2dc5a13b8ae20c1c73/0_0_1060_1364/777.jpg\" alt=\"The ounce and the linx from Topsell's The History of Four-footer Beasts and Serpents (1658)\" width=\"777\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">The royal menagerie at the Tower of London, was probably founded in 1204 when King John brought three shiploads of wild beasts (lions and leopards) to England from Normandy. In the early days most of the animals in the Tower came from north-west Africa, including the <em>Uncia</em> (leopards) and the <em>Linx</em> (probably a caracal cat), seen by the humanist scholar John Caius in 1561. Caius sent drawings of them to Conrad Gesner for his<em> Historiæ Animalium</em>, and images were reprinted in Topsell’s translation: <em>The History of Four-footed Beasts and Serpents</em> (1658)</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"4f6fe502d990d445799d3a336c60a7652804e26c\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/4f6fe502d990d445799d3a336c60a7652804e26c/0_0_3280_2121/1000.jpg\" alt=\"The Shah Goest\" width=\"1000\" height=\"647\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">When Clive of India heard that William Pitt had described him in the House of Commons as ‘a heaven-born general’, he sent Pitt a most unusual present – a caracal cat – which had been presented to him by the Nawab of Bengal’s treacherous general, Mir Jaffir. Pitt seems not to have been overjoyed for he quickly offered it to the King. According to Horace Walpole, ‘It is called in the Indostan language a Saah Goest … It is now in the Tower attended by a domestick of the Nabob’s, who was charged with the care of it to England.’</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Wellcome Library</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"06f0357cec21bbf7eb1157d09aa1a927ec98eaea\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/06f0357cec21bbf7eb1157d09aa1a927ec98eaea/0_0_1227_1955/628.jpg\" alt=\"A Malayan sun bear\" width=\"628\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Stamford Raffles, founder of Singapore and of the Zoological Society of London, sent this Malayan sun bear to the Tower in 1824, three years after he had published the first scientific description of this previously unknown species. It was described as ‘excessively voracious and appears to be disposed to eat almost without cessation’. Its greed was its undoing, for one day in the summer of 1828 it ‘over-gorged itself one day at breakfast and died’. Its stuffed skin ended up, appropriately, in the Zoological Society’s museum.</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"c2dab6f297421aeada85b99295553d67bcbcdcab\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/c2dab6f297421aeada85b99295553d67bcbcdcab/0_0_672_500/672.jpg\" alt=\"Greenland caribou\" width=\"672\" height=\"500\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">From the early 18th century onwards, increasing numbers of private individuals started collections of exotic animals. These were usually housed on country estates, but Hans Sloane kept a wide variety at his home in Chelsea, where the unusual household pets included a one-eyed wolverine from Hudson’s Bay. In 1738 Captain Craycott brought him a pair of caribou from Greenland, which were drawn by George Edwards before being sent on to the Duke of Richmond’s estate at Goodwood in the hope that they might breed. They died shortly afterwards.</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"ad0e50c20cdf61a6722cfde20e1c3d830d1affa7\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/ad0e50c20cdf61a6722cfde20e1c3d830d1affa7/0_0_2721_1938/1000.jpg\" alt=\"The Duke of Richmond’s Java Hare\" width=\"1000\" height=\"712\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">The Duke of Richmond’s menagerie included wolves and leopards, a lioness, a civet, a ‘tyger catt’, foxes, a jackal, two Greenland dogs, three vultures, two eagles, a kite, two owls, at least three bears, a ‘white’ bear, a large monkey, three raccoons, three small monkeys, an armadillo, a peccary, and seven cassowaries. Among his household pets was a ‘tame and inoffensive ... Java hare’ recorded for posterity in a 1747 edition of Mark Catesby’s <em>Natural History of Carolina</em>. It was neither a hare nor from Java – it was the first agouti from South America to be recorded in England.</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"d819517302f572ad9e3c65cdcb8cc790cc2af4ac\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/d819517302f572ad9e3c65cdcb8cc790cc2af4ac/0_0_1475_1781/828.jpg\" alt=\"The Gamboa Groasbeak\" width=\"828\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">The Duke of Chandos acquired Canons Park in 1713, and set about transforming the estate into one of the grandest in England, complete with a collection of exotic animals from Africa and the New World. His letters show that he had a genuine interest in animals, both his own and those that he had seen exhibited in London. He fed the cranes that stalked around the garden terraces with his own hand and allowed Eleazer Albin to study the birds in his famous aviary – ‘The Gamboa Groasbeak ... from coast of Guinea’, is described and illustrated in Albin’s <em>Natural History of Birds</em> (1738).</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"0707ce0f102974b03f1b7549d189a31d39b02cfd\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/0707ce0f102974b03f1b7549d189a31d39b02cfd/0_0_3068_2451/1000.jpg\" alt=\"A female zebra standing in an enclosure\" width=\"1000\" height=\"799\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Various members of the royal family kept collections of exotic animals on their estates at Richmond and Kew. During the 1740s, Frederick Prince of Wales was sent a pair of zebras from the Cape of Good Hope. The stallion died en route, but the mare lived at Kew for several years. George Edwards drew her in 1751, and published an engraving in his<em> Gleanings of Natural History</em>. This shows her with dark brown stripes on a brownish background which fade out towards her rump – the coloration of a quagga, extinct since 1883 and now considered to have been a sub-species of the plains zebra.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Wellcome Library</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"01262c1a3549fa847383af1155ce2ddc43d1e559\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/01262c1a3549fa847383af1155ce2ddc43d1e559/0_0_1481_2074/714.jpg\" alt=\"Hannah Twynnoy’s tombstone at Malmesbury Abbey\" width=\"714\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Exotic animals were not simply objects of enjoyment or curiosity, good money could be paid from exhibiting them ‘to be seen or sold’ at London pubs and fairs. An Indian elephant was shown at the Rising Star in 1675, an Indian rhinoceros at the Belle Sauvage in 1684, and a short-lived chimp, which had arrived with slaves from West Africa in 1698, was displayed at Moncrieff’s coffee house. Animals were occasionally shown in provincial towns, as Hannah Twynnoy’s tombstone at Malmesbury Abbey attests. Note the use of the generic term ‘tyger’ for most large cats – it was probably a leopard.</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"79c2ff8d343dd1fb2654d3dcb8f9d16b37f35442\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/79c2ff8d343dd1fb2654d3dcb8f9d16b37f35442/0_0_1188_827/1000.jpg\" alt=\"A ‘Numidian’ lion\" width=\"1000\" height=\"696\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">When Gilbert Pidcock’s travelling menagerie visited Newcastle in 1788, Edward Bewick took the opportunity to draw several of the animals, including this tame ‘Numidian’ lion from Algiers, described in advertisements as ‘one of the finest lions (very lately brought over)’. The resulting woodcut was published in his <em>General History of Quadrupeds </em>(1790).</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"6de18e2ae56ac61e3c626c3a5df9b70b54cf0f1f\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/6de18e2ae56ac61e3c626c3a5df9b70b54cf0f1f/0_0_1355_2568/528.jpg\" alt=\"Farthing from Pidcock’s menagerie\" width=\"528\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">The best known commercial menagerie of the late 18th and early 19th centuries was housed on the second floor of the Exeter Change on the Strand in London. It was started in 1778 by Thomas Clarke, and showed some of the first Australian marsupials seen in Britain, including a bettong (kangaroo-rat), a flying phalanger and a kangaroo. Pidcock took over the entire operation in 1793, promoting it with exuberant newspaper adverts and a flood of handbills. Dozens of coins like this two-sided farthing token were produced with images of the more spectacular animals, perhaps as keepsakes for visitors.</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"1c64f10cab2b6e7488c59bfcd53d5c0f0e8c809a\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/1c64f10cab2b6e7488c59bfcd53d5c0f0e8c809a/0_0_3072_2304/1000.jpg\" alt=\"An engraving of a boxing kangaroo\" width=\"1000\" height=\"750\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">More kangaroos arrived, not only at the Exeter Change, and soon began to breed, so that by 1805 Thomas Smith could remark that ‘these animals may now be considered as in some degree naturalized in England’. One of Pidcock’s largest kangaroos had ‘remarkable pugilistic skills’, Smith wrote. ‘I saw this noble quadruped wrestle with the keeper for the space of ten or fifteen minutes, during which time he evinced the utmost intrepidity and sagacity…’ This may be the first picture of what has since become a national symbol of Australia – the boxing kangaroo.</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"99de9aa11fdc1dfc922dbac52b1894045480c183\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/99de9aa11fdc1dfc922dbac52b1894045480c183/0_0_2109_1207/1000.jpg\" alt=\"A plains viscacha\" width=\"1000\" height=\"572\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">The menagerie at the Exeter Change was taken over successively by Stephen Polito in 1810 and Edward Cross in 1814, both of whom also toured some of the animals around the country. Cross owned mammals of scientific importance including this so-called marmot – illustrated, like many other animals from the Exeter Change in Edward Griffith’s edition of Georges Cuvier’s <em>The Animal Kingdom</em> (1827). It was actually a previously unknown species, the plains viscacha, first scientifically described by the surgeon Joshua Brookes in 1828.</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"e86370211f8d2cda8474d70bf65dad37d160f14e\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/e86370211f8d2cda8474d70bf65dad37d160f14e/0_0_1942_1014/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Clouded leopard\" width=\"1000\" height=\"522\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">The first clouded leopard known to science, said to have arrived from Canton in about 1817 and kept at the Exeter Change, was named by Edward Griffiths in 1821 as the ‘clouded tiger’. Its skin was lost to science because the animal was ‘taken into the country with an itinerant exhibition and died there, and so little attention did Zoology, at that time, receive here, that as far as appears, its skin was cut up to make caps for the keepers’.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Private collection</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"c81466a1d2c58489315bdfbaa30dff5e8d8f98fc\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/c81466a1d2c58489315bdfbaa30dff5e8d8f98fc/0_0_2249_1376/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Lady Castlereagh's 'black-maned' lion\" width=\"1000\" height=\"612\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Lady Castlereagh kept a menagerie at North Cray in Kent with a mocking bird, ‘nutmeg birds’, a flying squirrel, an antelope, several kangaroos, emus, a pair of ostriches and a puma or jaguar. Her husband liked to boast that he was the only person at the Coronation of George IV in 1821 who wore a plume of ostrich feathers from his own birds. Her magnificent ‘black-maned’ lion from South Africa was perhaps too dangerous to be kept at Cray – she gave it to Edward Cross at the Exeter Change, where it was drawn by Thomas Landseer. The resulting engraving was published by Griffiths in 1827.</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"227f13a40ce3f779dfcfb7c7ae0b6ce3ad4445d6\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/227f13a40ce3f779dfcfb7c7ae0b6ce3ad4445d6/0_35_931_1248/746.jpg\" alt=\"Flyer for Wombwell’s Royal Menagerie\" width=\"746\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">In 1831, after over 600 years of almost continuous operation, the menagerie at the Tower of London was closed and the animals moved to the newly-opened Zoological Gardens in Regent’s Park. Animals brought to England must have suffered terribly both on board ship and in their cramped cages on arrival, but – at the time of the transatlantic slave trade – were people treated any better? In 1850, George Wombwell’s obituary paid tribute to the educational value of his travelling menageries, arguing that ‘no one has done so much to forward practically the study of natural history among the masses’.</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"a78ca792278a34f087a918605386a7559e2f8bcd\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/a78ca792278a34f087a918605386a7559e2f8bcd/0_0_919_1418/648.jpg\" alt=\"Menagerie by Caroline Grigson\" width=\"648\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/jan/13/menagerie-the-history-of-exotic-animals-in-england-caroline-grigson-review\">Review: Menagerie by Caroline Grigson (OUP)</a><br><a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/362093/\">Buy it at the Guardian bookshop</a></span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: OUP</span> </figcaption> </figure>","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4h9gx","wordcount":"0","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/4f6fe502d990d445799d3a336c60a7652804e26c/112_140_3041_1826/140.jpg","commentCloseDate":"2016-03-30T23:00:00Z","standfirst":"<p>Exotic animals have been kept in Britain for more than eight centuries, inspiring wonder and terror in those who saw them – despite the cruelties of their captivity. The zoologist Caroline Grigson takes us on a tour of the UK’s historic animal visitors, from agouti to zebra</p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/gallery/2016/mar/15/animal-travellers-a-history-of-exotic-animals-in-the-uk-in-pictures","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/gallery/2016/mar/15/animal-travellers-a-history-of-exotic-animals-in-the-uk-in-pictures","sectionName":"Books","elements":[{"id":"1b3e9a15a341e2dd2a947c2dc5a13b8ae20c1c73","relation":"gallery","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/1b3e9a15a341e2dd2a947c2dc5a13b8ae20c1c73/0_0_1060_1364/1060.jpg","typeData":{"mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/1b3e9a15a341e2dd2a947c2dc5a13b8ae20c1c73","altText":"The ounce and the linx from Topsell's The History of Four-footer Beasts and Serpents (1658)","caption":"The royal menagerie at the Tower of London, was probably founded in 1204 when King John brought three shiploads of wild beasts (lions and leopards) to England from Normandy. In the early days most of the animals in the Tower came from north-west Africa, including the <em>Uncia</em> (leopards) and the <em>Linx</em> (probably a caracal cat), seen by the humanist scholar John Caius in 1561. Caius sent drawin