were not simply objects of enjoyment or curiosity, good money could be paid from exhibiting them ‘to be seen or sold’ at London pubs and fairs. An Indian elephant was shown at the Rising Star in 1675, an Indian rhinoceros at the Belle Sauvage in 1684, and a short-lived chimp, which had arrived with slaves from West Africa in 1698, was displayed at Moncrieff’s coffee house. Animals were occasionally shown in provincial towns, as Hannah Twynnoy’s tombstone at Malmesbury Abbey attests. Note the use of the generic term ‘tyger’ for most large cats – it was probably a leopard.","source":"Private collection","credit":"Photograph: Private collection","mediaId":"01262c1a3549fa847383af1155ce2ddc43d1e559","displayCredit":"false","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/01262c1a3549fa847383af1155ce2ddc43d1e559/0_0_1481_2074/357.jpg","width":"357","height":"500"},"mimeType":"image/jpeg"}]},{"id":"79c2ff8d343dd1fb2654d3dcb8f9d16b37f35442","relation":"gallery","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/79c2ff8d343dd1fb2654d3dcb8f9d16b37f35442/0_0_1188_827/1188.jpg","typeData":{"mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/79c2ff8d343dd1fb2654d3dcb8f9d16b37f35442","altText":"A ‘Numidian’ lion","caption":"When Gilbert Pidcock’s travelling menagerie visited Newcastle in 1788, Edward Bewick took the opportunity to draw several of the animals, including this tame ‘Numidian’ lion from Algiers, described in advertisements as ‘one of the finest lions (very lately brought over)’. The resulting woodcut was published in his <em>General History of Quadrupeds </em>(1790).","source":"Private collection","credit":"Photograph: Private collection","mediaId":"79c2ff8d343dd1fb2654d3dcb8f9d16b37f35442","displayCredit":"false","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/79c2ff8d343dd1fb2654d3dcb8f9d16b37f35442/0_0_1188_827/1188.jpg","width":"1188","height":"827"},"mimeType":"image/jpeg"},{"type":"image","file":"http://med