54cf0f1f/0_0_1355_2568/1355.jpg","typeData":{"mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/6de18e2ae56ac61e3c626c3a5df9b70b54cf0f1f","altText":"Farthing from Pidcock’s menagerie","caption":"The best known commercial menagerie of the late 18th and early 19th centuries was housed on the second floor of the Exeter Change on the Strand in London. It was started in 1778 by Thomas Clarke, and showed some of the first Australian marsupials seen in Britain, including a bettong (kangaroo-rat), a flying phalanger and a kangaroo. Pidcock took over the entire operation in 1793, promoting it with exuberant newspaper adverts and a flood of handbills. Dozens of coins like this two-sided farthing token were produced with images of the more spectacular animals, perhaps as keepsakes for visitors.","source":"Private collection","credit":"Photograph: Private collection","mediaId":"6de18e2ae56ac61e3c626c3a5df9b70b54cf0f1f","displayCredit":"false","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/6de18e2ae56ac61e3c626c3a5df9b70b54cf0f1f/0_0_1355_2568/1355.jpg","width":"1355","height":"2568"},"mimeType":"image/jpeg"},{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/6de18e2ae56ac61e3c626c3a5df9b70b54cf0f1f/0_0_1355_2568/master/1355.jpg","typeData":{"mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/6de18e2ae56ac61e3c626c3a5df9b70b54cf0f1f","altText":"Farthing from Pidcock’s menagerie","caption":"The best known commercial menagerie of the late 18th and early 19th centuries was housed on the second floor of the Exeter Change on the Strand in London. It was started in 1778 by Thomas Clarke, and showed some of the first Australian marsupials seen in Britain, including a bettong (kangaroo-rat), a flying phalanger and a kangaroo. Pidcock took over the entire operation in 1793, promoting it with exuberant newspaper adverts and a flood of handbills. Dozens of coins like this two-sided farthing token were produced with images of the more spectacular animals, perhaps as keeps