pis.com/type/article","references":[]},{"id":"tone/features","webTitle":"Features","type":"tone","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tone/features","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/tone/features","references":[]},{"id":"profile/samjordison","webTitle":"Sam Jordison","type":"contributor","bio":"<p>Sam Jordison is a co-director of Galley Beggar Press and the co-editor of the Crap Towns series of books. You can follow him <a href=\"https://twitter.com/samjordison\">@samjordison</a></p>","bylineImageUrl":"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2012/5/7/1336387144696/Sam-Jordison.jpg","firstName":"","lastName":"jordison","r2ContributorId":"16395","rcsId":"GNL033531","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/profile/samjordison","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/profile/samjordison","references":[]}],"references":[]},{"webPublicationDate":"2016-03-15T13:07:42Z","webTitle":"Ta-Nehisi Coates promises 'dramatic upheaval' in new Black Panther comic series","sectionId":"books","type":"article","rights":{"syndicatable":"true"},"id":"books/2016/mar/15/ta-nehisi-coates-promises-dramatic-upheaval-in-new-black-panther-comic-series","fields":{"commentable":"true","byline":"Alison Flood","headline":"Ta-Nehisi Coates promises 'dramatic upheaval' in new Black Panther comic series","trailText":"National Book award winner will use Marvel comic to pose questions about leadership and rebellions from pre-colonial Africa to the present day","productionOffice":"UK","body":"<p>The <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/nov/19/ta-nehisi-coates-wins-national-book-award-for-nonfiction\">National Book award-winning</a> writer Ta-Nehisi Coates says his forthcoming Black Panther comic is inspired by “the very real history of society”, from pre-colonial Africa to the rise of Islamic State.</p> <p>Coates is the recipient of a <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/sep/29/ta-nehisi-coates-macarthur-fellow-genius-grants\">MacArthur “genius” grant</a> and author of the bestselling exploration of race in the US, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/jul/14/between-the-world-and-me-ta-nehisi-coates-review\">Between the World and Me</a>. Last September, he was signed by Marvel to write <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/sep/22/ta-nehisi-coates-to-write-marvels-black-panther-comic\">a new series of Black Panther comics</a>, called A Nation Under Our Feet. The Black Panther character, T’Challa, is the head of the wealthy, technologically advanced African nation of Wakanda. When he made his debut on the page in 1966, he was the first mainstream black superhero.</p> <p>The first issue in the new series, illustrated by Brian Stelfreeze, is out on 6 April. Coates unveiled pages from the comic <a href=\"http://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2016/04/the-return-of-the-black-panther/471516/\">in the Atlantic</a>, where he wrote that in his journalism for the magazine he has “been asking a particular question: can a society part with, and triumph over, the very plunder that made it possible? </p>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--supporting\" data-media-id=\"bde050ba035a6ed9ec2d249740cb05362e417eb9\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/bde050ba035a6ed9ec2d249740cb05362e417eb9/0_339_2003_1201/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Ta-Nehisi Coates at the 2015 National Book awards in New York.\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Ta-Nehisi Coates at the 2015 National Book awards in New York.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Robin Platzer/Twin Images</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>“In Black Panther there is a simpler question: can a good man be a king, and would an advanced society tolerate a monarch?” he wrote. “Research is crucial in both cases. The Black Panther I offer pulls from the archives of Marvel and the character’s own long history. But it also pulls from the very real history of society – from the precolonial era of Africa, the peasant rebellions that wracked Europe toward the end of the middle ages, the American civil war, the Arab spring and the rise of Isis.”</p> <p>Marvel has said that in A Nation Under Our Feet there will be “dramatic upheaval” in Wakanda, as the Black Panther “struggles to do right by his people as their ruler”.</p> <p>“The indomitable will of Wakanda – the famed African nation known for its vast wealth, advanced technology and warrior traditions – has long been reflected in the will of its monarchs, the Black Panthers,” said the publisher. “Now the current Black Panther, T’Challa, finds that will tested by a superhuman terrorist group called the People that has sparked a violent uprising among the citizens of Wakanda. T’Challa knows the country must change to survive. The question is: will the Black Panther survive the change?”</p>  <figure class=\"element element-embed\" data-canonical-url=\"http://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2016/04/the-return-of-the-black-panther/471516/\" data-alt=\"Ta-Nehisi Coates speaks with the Atlantic about writing the forthcoming Black Panther series - video\">  <iframe src='http://www.theatlantic.com/video/embed/?brightcove_id=4792142562001' allowfullscreen frameborder=0></iframe> <figcaption>Ta-Nehisi Coates speaks with the Atlantic about writing the forthcoming Black Panther series</figcaption> </figure>  <p>Coates said in the Atlantic that comics were his “earliest influences”, and that when he was contacted about continuing the Black Panther series: “I was less concerned with character conflict than with the realisation of my dreams as a nine-year-old.</p> <p>“Some of the best days of my life were spent poring over the back issues of The Uncanny X-Men and The Amazing Spider-Man. As a child of the crack-riddled west Baltimore of the 1980s, I found the tales of comic books to be an escape, another reality where, very often, the weak and mocked could transform their fallibility into fantastic power,” wrote the author.</p> <p>“Chris Claremont’s The Uncanny X-\u001EMen wasn’t just about an ultracool band of rebels. That series sought to grapple with the role of minorities in society – both the inner power and the outward persecution that come with that status. And so it is, I hope, with Black Panther. The questions are what motivate the action. The questions, ultimately, are more necessary than the answers.”</p> <p>The character will also be appearing in the <a href=\"http://www.imdb.com/title/tt3498820/\">Captain America: Civil War film</a> this year, played by Chadwick Boseman, as well as in a <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/oct/28/marvel-black-panther-doctor-strange-avengers-movies-schedule\">forthcoming Black Panther</a> movie.</p>","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4hhzm","wordcount":"574","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/a886265ac69e192181b46fe6dd09f04e8ffb96ea/33_476_598_359/140.jpg","commentCloseDate":"2016-03-22T00:00:00Z","standfirst":"<p>National Book award winner will use Marvel comic to pose questions about leadership and rebellions from pre-colonial Africa to the present day</p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/mar/15/ta-nehisi-coates-promises-dramatic-upheaval-in-new-black-panther-comic-series","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/2016/mar/15/ta-nehisi-coates-promises-dramatic-upheaval-in-new-black-panther-comic-series","sectionName":"Books","elements":[{"id":"a886265ac69e192181b46fe6dd09f04e8ffb96ea","relation":"main","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/a886265ac69e192181b46fe6dd09f04e8ffb96ea/0_474_659_489/140.jpg","typeData":{"mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/a886265ac69e192181b46fe6dd09f04e8ffb96ea","altText":"A preview of Ta-Nehisi Coates' Black Panther comic for Marvel","caption":"A preview of Ta-Nehisi Coates’ Black Panther comic.","source":"Marvel","credit":"Photograph: Marvel","mediaId":"a886265ac69e192181b46fe6dd09f04e8ffb96ea","displayCredit"