Striped Pyjamas. So when Gavriel visited the UK last month, from his home in the United States, we persuaded him to pay a visit to Guardian Towers and record this fascinating podcast. Teen site members Lottie is Dottie and Ayesha (who found the book “more complicated than Hamlet”), got to ask him all about his beautiful, complex novel and ask why it doesn’t give any easy answers – as well as explore why children’s authors mustn’t be afraid to go into dark places. </p> <p>Also read <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2015/dec/23/anna-and-the-swallow-man-gavriel-savit-review\">Ayesha’s review of Anna and the Swallow Man</a> – and also check out <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2015/dec/09/anna-and-the-swallow-man-gavriel-savit-review\">Nava4’s review: “a compelling and thought-provoking read”</a>, and SophieScribe’s warning that <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2016/jan/03/anna-and-the-swallow-man-gavriel-savit-review\">you need your tissues when reading</a>. </p> <p>Also do read <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2016/jan/27/remembering-the-people-of-the-holocaust\">Remembering the people of the Holocaust</a>, which Gavriel wrote for this year’s Holocaust Memorial Day. </p> <p>We’ll leave you with a quote from Gavriel: “I’ve never encountered a person who has been traumatised by a book when they were young”.</p>","productionOffice":"UK","trailText":"Harrowing second world war tale Anna and the Swallow Man has taken teen readers by storm. Teen site members Lottie is Dottie and Ayesha got to ask the author about the mythologisation of the Holocaust, deep and dark things, stories without end and the meaning of life","headline":"Gavriel Savit: 'I’ve never known the end of a chapter in my life' - children's books podcast","byline":"Gavriel Savit, Lottie is Dottie and Ayesha, presented by Emily Drabble and produced by Rowan Slaney"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-