theguardian.com/profile/ben-okri","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/profile/ben-okri","references":[]}],"references":[]},{"webPublicationDate":"2016-03-15T09:30:00Z","webTitle":"The Modernist Papers by Fredric Jameson review – weighty essays on literature and art","sectionId":"books","type":"article","rights":{"syndicatable":"true"},"id":"books/2016/mar/15/modernist-papers-fredric-jameson-review","fields":{"commentable":"true","byline":"Nicholas Lezard","headline":"The Modernist Papers by Fredric Jameson review – weighty essays on literature and art","trailText":"Proust or Joyce? I may be long past my university days, but I am still a sucker for this kind of question","productionOffice":"UK","body":"<p>There were times when I asked myself why I was reading this collection of essays on modernist literature spanning three decades, and why, moreover, I was recommending it to you, oh gentle and blameless reader. What grudge do I have against you, or what atonement do I think I am performing, when I run up against a sentence like the following? “The preconditions for the autonomy of the aesthetic totality can be formulated in a different way, in terms of the problem of reference.” And I should add that this is one of Professor Jameson’s shorter sentences. The next one is four times as long and mentions <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2000/jul/16/biography.philosophy\" title=\"\">Hegel</a>, and whenever I run across that name I feel like tiptoeing off to the drinks cabinet and pouring myself a stiff one.</p> <p>But, but. The sentence I quote comes from a chapter called “Proust or Joyce?” and I must confess that I am a sucker for that kind of question. I may be long past my university days, which was the last time I might have been expected to consider such a question, but when I see a book that asks it – or, as in another chapter, whether <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/charles-baudelaire\" title=\"\">Baudelaire</a> was a modernist, and if so what kind; or which tantalisingly offers the prospect of getting a handle on Wallace Stevens’s beautifully baffling verse – then I am drawn to it, as the moth to the light bulb. And if I batter myself senselessly against it with at times as little comprehension as the moth has of the concept of electricity, then I will at least have had the benefit of some light.</p> <p>Jameson has been publishing since 1961, and has now written so many books that you may have picked one up yourself. A Marxist thinker who throws out terms like “dialectical” a lot, he nevertheless is capable of letting the mask slip and producing something that is readable, and at times charmingly so. For example, on <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/2002/aug/24/art\" title=\"\">De Kooning</a> (like many literary critics, Jameson is very good on art; there’s a playfulness at work when the literary sensibility bumps into the image, like a bring-your-toys-to-school day): “What I like to look at in De Kooning’s paintings is the yellow. I like to look at the yellow parts of even those paintings I don’t think much of. Next to the yellow, I like to look at the pink. Finally the grey.” Was there ever a more winning introduction to a serious essay on aesthetics? And it leads, by plausible and convincing steps, to this conclusion: “Photorealism is thus the aesthetic ideology and the fullest living expression of that sterile thing which is consumer capitalism or the s<em>ocieté de consommation</em>.” (Note the teasing opposition of “fullest living expression” and “sterile thing”; almost, but not quite, completely contradictory.)</p> <p>The large part of Jameson’s career has involved explaining the “catastrophe” of postmodernism, and not only does anyone who uses such a word to describe PoMo make me prick up my ears, it also means that they are going to engage with what came before the “post”: <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/marcelproust\" title=\"\">Proust</a>, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/jamesjoyce\" title=\"\">Joyce</a>, Stevens, James and Mallarmé, to mention just some of the writers dealt with here. And if he has the cheek to name “the two most boring chapters in <em>Ulysses</em>”, he also has the grace to make the case for them. Quoting the penultimate chapter of Joyce’s novel, he says he actually “tend[s] rather to prefer this one” to Molly Bloom’s monologue. (So do I.)</p> <p>Effort is rewarding in itself, and there are tougher challenges than reading Jameson. “As I read those three thousand pages …” he says, referring to Sartre’s unfinished magnum opus on Flaubert, and overhead passes a nightmare that has not settled upon us. He has read those three thousand pages so we don’t have to.</p> <p>• To order <em>The Modernist Papers</em> for £14.99 go to <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/373179/?utm_source=editoriallink&amp;utm_medium=merch&amp;utm_campaign=article\" title=\"\">bookshop.theguardian.com</a> or call 0330 333 6846. Free UK p&amp;p over £10, online orders only. Phone orders min p&amp;p of £1.99.</p>","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4hh9n","wordcount":"716","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/1f6ebef0249f2475d14821ea3e6c25aacc394ffd/0_306_2321_1397/140.jpg","commentCloseDate":"2016-04-29T15:58:00Z","standfirst":"Proust or Joyce? I may be long past my university days, but I am still a sucker for this kind of question"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/mar/15/modernist-papers-fredric-jameson-review","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/2016/mar/15/modernist-papers-fredric-jameson-review","sectionName":"Books","elements":[{"id":"1f6ebef0249f2475d14821ea3e6c25aacc394ffd","relation":"main","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/1f6ebef0249f2475d14821ea3e6c25aacc394ffd/0_306_2321_1397/2000.jpg","typeData":{"copyright":"AP2010","picdarUrn":"GD*26456542","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/1f6ebef0249f2475d14821ea3e6c25aa