awn, I can never get them out of my head. Even now, whenever I see a train bound for Cardiff, I picture Kate, the heroine of her third novel, <em>The Master Bedroom</em>. What is she doing these days, I think to myself. Is she sleeping with yet another unsuitable man?</p> <p>If you haven’t read Hadley before, where should you start? My favourite book of hers is <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/clever-girl.html\"><em>Clever Girl</em></a>, from 2013, which tells the story of Stella in 10 seemingly self-contained chapters from her childhood in the 1960s through to her married middle age. It’s a remarkable novel, not least for the seamless way Hadley handles the passage of time, though its chief bit of daring for me is its expression of what cleverness feels like, and the impact this may have on the trajectory of an ordinary woman’s life. It should enrich, and mostly it does, but it also increases the chances that she will feel patronised or, even worse, thwarted.</p> <p>Stella struggles with life. Things often go wrong for her. Yet somehow, she is always heading towards the light. I remember that I found this almost unbearably moving; I read the novel’s last 30 pages with tears rolling down my cheeks, a rare thing for me. And when <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/sep/06/tessa-hadley-meet-the-author-the-past\">I interviewed Hadley</a> last summer, before the publication of her latest novel, <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/323074/s/the-past/\"><em>The Past</em></a>, I was ambushed by the memory of it. As her creator looked on kindly, I struggled to compose myself, Stella having suddenly crept, quite uninvited, into her sun-filled sitting room.</p>","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4hazm","wordcount":"390","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/442d5509026b332b116da31ba0a2cba8fa630df2/0_62_5616_3371/140.jpg","commentCloseDate":"2016-04-03T10:20:00Z","standfirst":"<p>Few writers can create female characters like Tessa Ha